{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1784323596,"nonce":"INrdnvzrZZ4CIRI/avya0iEiMgs=","message":"The trigger-wipe is now LOUD — PR #110 (squash 5717941). It is NOT preserved; see the caveat at the end.\n\nSQLite has no CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW, so a view change applies as DROP VIEW + CREATE\nVIEW, and DROP VIEW takes the view's INSTEAD OF triggers with it. squealy has no trigger\nmodel, so nothing recreates them.\n\nA finding worse than this bug describes drove the design: the bug frames it as \"a CHANGED\nview loses its triggers\", but a Safe-classified AddCheck, under the DEFAULT (risk-blocking)\npolicy, silently wipes triggers on an UNCHANGED, unrelated view — and the plan never\nmentions the view at all. SQLite cannot ALTER ... ADD CONSTRAINT, so it rebuilds the table,\nand the renderer drops the transitive closure of collateral views to survive the rebuild\n(PR #98). The root defect is that CreateView is classified ChangeRisk::Safe unconditionally\n— true on PG/MySQL (CREATE OR REPLACE), false on SQLite (DROP + CREATE). Both paths were\nreproduced before coding.\n\nFix (maintainer-chosen: \"make it loud\", check in the SQLite backend, gated on the existing\nDiffPolicy.allow_destructive): a new defaulted seam DdlExecutor::execute_plan_ddl runs the\nbatch's DDL with the plan that produced it; SQLite overrides it to ask its own renderer for\nthe drop set (the extracted plan_view_drops, now shared with write_plan so the two cannot\ndisagree) and query the live catalog for triggers on those views, refusing with an error\nthat names them. The check runs inside the batch's own transaction so a concurrently-created\ntrigger cannot slip through. With allow_destructive the apply proceeds and the trigger is\ngone — the caller's choice, not a silent loss.\n\nPreserving the triggers is deliberately NOT attempted: PR #81's round 14 is a general proof\nthat replaying captured trigger DDL cannot be validated without modelling the trigger body\n(a batch can rebuild a base table, leave the view byte-identical, and leave the trigger body\nreferencing dropped columns). Refusing loudly is the honest promise until triggers are\nmodelled.\n\ncodex 2 rounds: R1 found three real holes, each reproduced then fixed — TEMP triggers live\nin sqlite_temp_master (DROP VIEW kills them too); the check/DDL race (moved inside the\ntransaction); ASCII-only identifier folding (\"Ä\"/\"ä\" are distinct views). R2 clean.\n\nVerified: fmt; clippy -D warnings; 965 tests / 0 failed; compile_fail; live PG 4/4,\nMySQL 11/11, squealy-model 7/7, CLI 11/11 (fresh db each). CI test + MSRV green.\n\nCLOSING SCOPE CAVEAT: this closes the SILENT-LOSS footgun, not the trigger family. A genuine\nchange to a trigger-carrying view is now refused rather than preserved. Actually preserving\nINSTEAD OF triggers across a view/table rebuild still needs a trigger model + reverse-parsed\ntrigger bodies — epic acb1c6d Phase 3 — which in turn needs a DML statement IR squealy-ir\ndoes not yet have (lower_query bottoms out at ViewBody). Closing this bug as \"made loud\";\nthe preservation work lives under the epic. Recommend the epic checklist note that Phase 3's\ntrigger item is a step-zero IR widening, not the independent slice the roadmap implies.","files":null}]}